ce:section.ce:para:
Electrochemical selective detection of biological samples remains challenging due to their electrode passivation and biofouling. The real-time quantitative determination of cellular Cys-is a crucial factor for biosystem because of an effective biomarker for various diseases [8]. There are two major pathways for detection of endogenous production of cellular Cys-like biochemical conversion (serine with methionine) and tryptophan synthase (serine and NaHS) [9]. The present study, tryptophan synthase was potentially used for the continuous detection of cellular Cys. Fig. 6C shows the real-time quantification of cellular Cys-in E. coli W3110 at GQDs-AuNPs-MFOF/GCE by DPV. No current responses were performed in E. coli W3110 (curve a), serine (curve b) and NaHS alone (curve c). On the other hand, current signal response was observed at E
                        pa = + 0.23 V, after the addition of serine and NaHS in E. coli W3110 with LB medium (curve d). Then, the addition of 100 µM of N-ethylmaleimide (NEM) to the same working solution, the current response was significantly masked due to their strong scavenger effect of NEM (curve e). The schematic representation of endogenous production of Cys-from live E. coli cells (Scheme 2
                        ).
